Assignment 6¶

In this assignment, you'll analyze a collection of data sets from the San Francisco Open Data Portal and Zillow. The data sets have been stored in the SQLite database sf_data.sqlite, which you can download here. The database contains the following tables:

Table Description
crime Crime reports dating back to 2010.
mobile_food_locations List of all locations where mobile food vendors sell.
mobile_food_permits List of all mobile food vendor permits. More details here.
mobile_food_schedule Schedules for mobile food vendors.
noise Noise complaints dating back to August 2015.
parking List of all parking lots.
parks List of all parks.
schools List of all schools.
zillow Zillow rent and housing statistics dating back to 1996. More details here.

The mobile_food_ tables are explicitly connected through the locationid and permit columns. The other tables are not connected, but you may be able to connect them using dates, latitude/longitude, or postal codes.

Shapefiles for US postal codes are available here. These may be useful for converting latitude/longitude to postal codes.

Shapefiles for San Francisco Neighborhoods are available here.

Exercise 1.1. Which mobile food vendor(s) sells at the most locations?

In [8]:
vendors = pd.read_sql_query("Select DISTINCT s.locationid, s.permit, p.Applicant from  mobile_food_schedule s " 
                  "LEFT JOIN mobile_food_permits p ON p.permit = s.permit;",sf_conn)

We find that May Catering sells at the most locations (58)! our initial SQL argument searched for the distinct location IDs in the mobile_food_schedule (since it duplicates itself for times) and also took the permit values and joined it with the permits from mobile_food_permits and the names of the places. I then put that into a pandas data frame and then took the count of them all

Exercise 1.2. Ask and use the database to analyze 5 questions about San Francisco. For each question, write at least 150 words and support your answer with plots. Make a map for at least 2 of the 5 questions.

You should try to come up with some questions on your own, but these are examples of reasonable questions:

  • Which parts of the city are the most and least expensive?
  • Which parts of the city are the most dangerous (and at what times)?
  • Are noise complaints and mobile food vendors related?
  • What are the best times and places to find food trucks?
  • Is there a relationship between housing prices and any of the other tables?

Please make sure to clearly state each of your questions in your submission.

What are the Rental Prices in each zip code?¶

regionprice = pd.read_sql_query("Select RegionName, AVG(ZriPerSqft_AllHomes) From zillow GROUP BY RegionName",
                                sf_conn)
regionprice = regionprice.dropna()
regionprice['RegionName']=regionprice['RegionName'].astype(str)

<mpl_toolkits.basemap.Basemap at 0x1996a3160>

Above we see a mapping done of the Zillow Rent Index per square foot in San Francisco (plus South San Francisco) with it organized per zip code area. First, the zillow data was taken from multiple days so I took the average of price per square foot of all homes in order to get an overall average. This data is from 2010 to 2017 measured monthly since this is a metric made by Zillow in order to measure the median rent in a region. How this metric is measured can be found online but it involves machine learning methods and other methods to find out the estimated rent. I believe it is fine to not include sold homes since San Francisco is very much a place where people rent instead of buy a home today. We also see that prices are very high in the waterfront areas near downtown and on the Embarcadero and decrease as you get further from the city center. This makes sense as it becomes more of a hassle to travel into the city for employment if you live on the outskirts of the city rather than the inner parts. I am somewhat surprised that the zip code near Golden Gate Park is not higher though since it is near an important place there.

Analysis¶

In the above metric we see the overall turnover rate of homes from 1998 to 2017 in San Francisco. I took an average of the turnover so some places may be higher than others. In this we see that there are some specific dips and rises that should be paid attention to in order to make assumptions about the health of the San Franciso Housing market. First, Turnover is the percentage of all homes in an area sold in the past month. If this is high then it means lots of people are selling their homes and lots of people are purchasing them as well. When it is low, this could be a supply or a demand issue, either nobody wants to buy the houses (low demand) or nobody wants to sell the houses (low supply). In San Franciso though there is the common knowldege that housing prices are one of the highest in the country meaning that the main issue in at least today is that nobody wants to sell or that supply is low.
First though, lets look at some history, we see dips primary in 2001 and 2008 which were obviously demand issues with 2001 being the burst of the .com bubble and 2008 being the Great Recession, both times people could not afford to buy a home. This soon peaked in 2013 with the tech industry reviving and then plummets as housing that was purchased is more than likely rented out by holding companies instead of lived in by individuals, becoming the supply issue. This shows that there needs to be more housing built in San Francisco in order to help alleviate this immedately.

From this map we can see where the parks and schools in San Francisco are. One of the more surprising results was the density of some of the parks and school as you get closer to the city center with many being very close to each other while as you get further from the city center, there is more distance between the schools. Another surprise is that some neighborhoods have only one or two schools or parks which makes some sense due to the fact that SF has significantly less children since the tech boom restarted back up due to rising housing prices again. This only shows where schools are and not the enrollment however, meaning that some of these may be very small private or charter schools for the wealthy elite and not classic public schools. Another surprise is that there are 2 schools on Treasure island. I did not even know schools were there really.

In this we see that the max is the South of Market Neighborhood for noise complaints which also has a large number of mobile food locations. However, it is rash to assume that they bring excess noise since we see in the South East part of town and along the Embarcadero there are a lot of mobile food locations but they too have low noise complaints in those neighborhoods. In fact, in the western district we see it is the 3rd noisiest (I believe it is the sunset district) but there are no mobile food locations inside its borders, only 4 along the edge, but it is a major residential part of San Francisco. It seems most Mobile food locations follow tourists which comes with traffic and other nuisances that could be the main reason for the noise complaints. As well, this map is only total number of noise complaints and does not control for population living in each district, normalized, this could be very different.

<mpl_toolkits.basemap.Basemap at 0x16b2b0b70>

In this chart we see plotted locations of crimes as of 6 months ago (9/18/16), which surprisingly gave us only results from 2017. (crimes since 2010 made the map completely blue) I also went about filtering out non-criminal, runaways, warrants, Driving Under the Influence, and Other offences. This still gives us a ton of crimes which is fairly concerning if you are going to pay an arm and a leg to live in this city but alas. We see the relationship is fairly strong with most crimes being around the embarcadero and the City Center and tapering out as you get further from the City Center. However, this makes logical sense that places with foot traffic would have more crime and that the same places with more foot traffic would be a GREAT place to have a mobile food location. This relation makes it difficult to come to a distinct conclusion to this question but I will say that SF has a TON of crime. and that one sector that shows that mobile food locations have little relation is on the border of the one district without crime in the north where there is a bundle of mobile food locations with very little crime in the area surounding it.
